('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'Which AWS code governs structural steel welding for buildings and bridges?', 'AWS D1.1', 'AWS D1.2', 'AWS D14.1', 'AWS D17.1', 'A', 'AWS D1.1 Structural Welding Code — Steel covers welding requirements for structural steel construction.', 'AWS D1.1:2020', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'AWS D1.1 covers base metal of what minimum thickness?', '1/16 in', '1/8 in', '3/16 in', '1/4 in', 'B', 'AWS D1.1 §1.1.1 specifies the code applies to welded steel structures with base metal 1/8 inch thick or greater.', 'AWS D1.1 §1.1', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'A WPS must be qualified by:', 'A welder', 'A PQR (Procedure Qualification Record)', 'The customer', 'OSHA', 'B', 'A non-prequalified WPS must be supported by a PQR documenting the test results that qualified the procedure.', 'AWS D1.1 §6', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'Per AWS D1.1, the maximum allowable undercut for statically loaded material under 1 inch thick is:', '1/32 in', '1/16 in', '1/8 in', '3/16 in', 'A', 'AWS D1.1 Table 6.1 limits undercut on statically loaded structures with material under 1 inch thick to 1/32 in.', 'AWS D1.1 Table 6.1', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'Cracks in any AWS D1.1 weld are:', 'Acceptable if small', 'Acceptable if not in tension', 'Never acceptable', 'Acceptable if peened', 'C', 'AWS D1.1 §6.9 explicitly prohibits all cracks regardless of size or location.', 'AWS D1.1 §6.9', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'A visual inspector should perform inspection:', 'Only after welding is complete', 'Before, during, and after welding', 'Only when called', 'Only on samples', 'B', 'Effective visual inspection covers fit-up before welding, monitoring during welding, and final inspection.', 'AWS D1.1 §6', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'weld_symbols', 'A weld symbol below the reference line indicates the weld is on the:', 'Other side of the joint', 'Arrow side of the joint', 'Both sides', 'Centerline', 'B', 'AWS A2.4: weld symbols below the reference line are arrow-side; symbols above are other-side.', 'AWS A2.4', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'weld_symbols', 'A flag symbol at the junction of the arrow and reference line indicates:', 'Field weld', 'Weld all around', 'Reject', 'Tack weld', 'A', 'A flag symbol at the junction indicates a field weld (welded in place rather than in the shop).', 'AWS A2.4', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'weld_symbols', 'A circle at the junction of the arrow and reference line indicates:', 'Field weld', 'Weld all around', 'Spot weld', 'Plug weld', 'B', 'A circle at the junction indicates "weld all around" — the weld continues around the perimeter of the joint.', 'AWS A2.4', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'metallurgy', 'Hydrogen-induced cracking (cold cracking) typically occurs:', 'Immediately during welding', 'Hours or days after welding', 'Only at high temperatures', 'Only on stainless steel', 'B', 'HIC (delayed cracking) typically appears 24-48 hours after welding as hydrogen diffuses to high-stress regions.', 'AWS D1.1', 'hard'),
('CAWI', 'metallurgy', 'The carbon equivalent (CE) formula is used to:', 'Calculate weld cost', 'Estimate hardenability and preheat needs', 'Determine electrode size', 'Set travel speed', 'B', 'CE estimates a steel''s susceptibility to hardening and cracking in the HAZ, helping determine preheat requirements.', 'AWS D1.1 Annex', 'hard'),
('CAWI', 'processes', 'Spray transfer GMAW requires:', 'Short circuit settings', 'Argon-rich shielding gas (>80% Ar) and high amperage', 'Pure CO2 only', 'AC current', 'B', 'Spray transfer requires high voltage/amperage with argon-rich shielding gas (typically 90/10 or 95/5 Ar/CO2) above the transition current.', 'AWS A3.0', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'API 1104 governs welding of:', 'Building structural steel', 'Pipelines for oil and gas transmission', 'Pressure vessels', 'Aerospace components', 'B', 'API 1104 is the standard for welding of pipelines and related facilities for oil and gas transmission.', 'API 1104', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'ASME Section IX governs:', 'Structural steel inspection', 'Welding and brazing qualifications for ASME code work', 'Pipeline welding', 'Aluminum welding', 'B', 'ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code Section IX covers welding, brazing, and fusing qualifications for ASME-stamped equipment.', 'ASME Section IX', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'Underfill on a groove weld is:', 'Acceptable if minor', 'Not permitted', 'Required by AWS D1.1', 'A normal condition', 'B', 'Per AWS D1.1, underfill (the weld face below the base metal surface) is not permitted on groove welds.', 'AWS D1.1 §6.9', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'ndt', 'Magnetic particle testing (MT) detects:', 'Subsurface volumetric defects', 'Surface and near-surface discontinuities in ferromagnetic materials', 'Internal porosity', 'Stainless steel cracks', 'B', 'MT detects surface-breaking and slightly subsurface discontinuities in ferromagnetic materials. It cannot inspect austenitic stainless or aluminum.', 'AWS B5.16', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'ndt', 'Radiographic testing (RT) is best for detecting:', 'Surface cracks only', 'Volumetric defects like porosity and inclusions', 'Surface roughness', 'Heat-affected zone hardness', 'B', 'RT excels at detecting volumetric defects (porosity, slag, voids) but is less reliable for tight planar defects oriented perpendicular to the beam.', 'ASNT', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'ndt', 'Ultrasonic testing (UT) is best for:', 'Surface inspection only', 'Detecting planar defects like lack of fusion', 'Aesthetic evaluation', 'Measuring hardness', 'B', 'UT is highly sensitive to planar defects (lack of fusion, cracks) that are difficult to detect with RT.', 'ASNT', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'processes', 'GMAW transfer modes include:', 'Short circuit only', 'Short circuit, globular, spray, pulsed', 'Only spray and globular', 'AC and DC only', 'B', 'GMAW has four primary metal transfer modes: short circuit, globular, spray, and pulsed spray.', 'AWS A3.0', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'metallurgy', 'Lamellar tearing is associated with:', 'Tension perpendicular to the rolling direction of plate', 'Aluminum welding', 'Tig welding', 'High preheat', 'A', 'Lamellar tearing occurs in plate when through-thickness tensile stress acts on planes of inclusions parallel to the rolling direction.', 'AWS D1.1', 'hard'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'Convexity of a fillet weld is measured:', 'Across the throat', 'From the hypotenuse line between toes to the highest point of the weld face', 'Across the leg length', 'From root to crown', 'B', 'AWS A3.0 defines convexity as the maximum distance from the face of a convex fillet weld to a line between the toes.', 'AWS A3.0', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'AWS D1.6 governs welding of:', 'Carbon steel', 'Stainless steel', 'Aluminum', 'Sheet steel', 'B', 'AWS D1.6 Structural Welding Code — Stainless Steel governs structural welding of stainless steel.', 'AWS D1.6', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'AWS D1.2 governs welding of:', 'Carbon steel', 'Stainless steel', 'Aluminum', 'Cast iron', 'C', 'AWS D1.2 Structural Welding Code — Aluminum governs structural welding of aluminum.', 'AWS D1.2', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'A fillet weld with insufficient throat thickness is:', 'Acceptable if leg length is correct', 'Rejectable', 'Stronger than designed', 'A normal condition', 'B', 'Throat thickness is the critical dimension for fillet weld strength; insufficient throat is rejectable.', 'AWS D1.1', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'weld_symbols', 'In a weld symbol, the dimensions appear:', 'Above the reference line only', 'To the left of the symbol for size, right for length', 'Inside the arrow', 'In the tail', 'B', 'Per AWS A2.4, size dimensions appear to the left of the weld symbol and length/pitch to the right.', 'AWS A2.4', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'processes', 'Submerged arc welding (SAW) uses:', 'A non-consumable tungsten', 'Granular flux that covers the arc', 'External shielding gas only', 'Coated electrode', 'B', 'SAW uses a continuous wire electrode under a layer of granular flux. The flux shields the arc from atmosphere.', 'AWS A3.0', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'safety', 'Hot work permits are typically required:', 'For welding in any production environment', 'Only in confined spaces', 'Never', 'Only on weekends', 'A', 'NFPA 51B and most facility safety programs require hot work permits for welding, cutting, and grinding outside of designated areas.', 'NFPA 51B', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'visual_inspection', 'A weld inspector should review the WPS:', 'After welding', 'Before welding starts and reference it during inspection', 'Only if asked', 'Only for new welders', 'B', 'The WPS defines acceptable procedures and parameters; the inspector must verify it is followed throughout welding.', 'AWS B5.1', 'easy'),
('CAWI', 'codes_standards', 'A welder qualification (WPQ) certifies the:', 'Welding procedure', 'Welder''s ability to follow a specific WPS', 'Base material', 'Inspector', 'B', 'WPQ documents that an individual welder has demonstrated the ability to produce sound welds following a qualified WPS.', 'AWS D1.1 §6', 'medium'),
('CAWI', 'metallurgy', 'Austenitic stainless steel is:', 'Magnetic', 'Non-magnetic in annealed condition', 'Always magnetic', 'Hardenable by heat treatment', 'B', '300-series austenitic stainless steels (304, 316) are non-magnetic in the annealed condition. Cold work can induce slight magnetism.', 'AWS D1.6', 'medium'),

